      "Drywall changed residential construction by replacing slower plaster-and-lath walls with factory-made gypsum panels that could be installed quickly, finished smoothly, and repaired predictably. Gypsum board became common in the 20th century because it reduced labor time, provided a consistent fire-resistant core, and made interior walls easier to build at scale. Today drywall is used in bedrooms, basements, garages, commercial interiors, ceilings, fire-rated assemblies, and moisture-prone spaces when the correct board type is selected.",
